attributes.description: Herpetological Associates initiated an ecological survey of the status and distribution of the Northern Pine Snake in New Jersey on May 13th 1977. Field work continued until October 1977 when the last specimen was found at its hibernaculum. Three hundred and eighty-five man-hours were spent in the field collecting and observing Northern Pine Snakes. They are known from eight counties in southern New Jersey. We decided to concentrate our efforts in Monmouth, Ocean, Burlington and Atlantic counties in 1977 and will expand into Camden, Gloucester, Cumberland and Cape May counties in the future. Nesting sites were discovered by HA staff members Zigmund Leszczynski and George Psaltis in Ocean County. These areas were monitored throughout the year and it was learned that one of the nesting sites was also used as a hibernaculum. Information has been gathered on population density, breeding habits, nesting behavior, egg laying, clutch size, incubation period, size of hatchlings, adult activity and hibernation. A total of 34 adult Pine Snakes were collected by HA staff members throughout the year.Five additional specimens were seen by members of the Philadelphia and New York Herpetological Societies and were included in the location data.The curators of the New Jersey State Museum and Newark Museum contributed additional locations.
